# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blue-plaque
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] Harrison lived in the property for seven years, by the end of which his family had been living there for nearly 20 years.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] They finally moved out to 25 Upton Green in the Speke district of Liverpool in 1950.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] Harrison recalled that the only heating was a single coal fire, and the house was so cold in winter that he and his brothers dreaded getting up in the morning because it was freezing cold and they had to use the outside toilet.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] The house had tiny rooms – only ten feet by ten (three metres by three; 100 ft2, about 9 m2) – and a small iron cooking stove in the back room, which was used as a kitchen.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] Harrison once said of the house, "Try and imagine the soul entering the womb of a woman living at 12 Arnold Grove, Wavertree, Liverpool 15.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] There were all the barrage balloons, and the Germans bombing Liverpool.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] I sat outside the house a couple of years ago, imagining 1943, nipping through the spiritual world, the astral level, getting back into a body in that house.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] That really is strange when you consider the whole planet, all the planets there may be on a spiritual level.
[src:blue-plaque/12-arnold-grove] In February 2024, it was announced that the home would receive a blue plaque, one of the first located outside of London; this was installed on 24 May 2024.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:blue-plaque/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The **East India Company Military Seminary** was a British military academy at Addiscombe, Surrey, in what is now the London Borough of Croydon.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Its purpose was to train young officers to serve in the East India Company's own army in India.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The institution was formally known as the **East India Company Military Seminary** (a name the cadets always disliked) until 1855, when the name was changed to the **East India Company Military College**.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In 1858, when the college was taken over by the government, it was renamed the **Royal India Military College**.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Colloquially, it was known as Addiscombe Seminary, Addiscombe College, or Addiscombe Military Academy.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Seminary was a sister institution to the East India Company College in Hertfordshire, which trained civilian "writers" (clerks).
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In military terms it was a counterpart to the Royal Military Academy at Woolwich and the Royal Military College at Sandhurst.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Addiscombe Place, the mansion house which formed the central building of the later Seminary, was erected in about 1702 by William Draper, on land which he had inherited in 1700 from his aunt, Dame Sarah Temple.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Draper's father-in-law was the diarist John Evelyn, who in 1703 pronounced the house "in all points of good and solid architecture to be one of the very best gentleman's houses in Surrey, when finish'd".
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Its interior included many mural paintings of mythological subjects, supposed to be the work of Sir James Thornhill; while high up on the exterior east front was carved the Latin inscription, *Non faciam vitio culpave minorem* ("I will not lower myself by vice or fault").
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] By the late 18th century the house was in the ownership of Charles James Clarke, who leased it to the statesman Charles Jenkinson, Lord Hawkesbury, later 1st Earl of Liverpool.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Regular visitors during Liverpool's tenure included King George III and William Pitt.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Following the death of Lord Liverpool in December 1808, Addiscombe Place was put on the market by Emelius Delmé-Radcliffe (Clarke's brother-in-law).
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] It was bought by the Court of Directors of the East India Company for use as a military academy.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Although the company was primarily a trading concern, it also maintained its own army, the officers of which had previously been trained at the Royal Military Academy, Woolwich, at the Royal Military College Junior Department at Great Marlow, or privately.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] They were now to be trained at Addiscombe.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Seminary opened on 21 January 1809, although the formal transfer of title of the property did not take place until a year later, on 26 January 1810.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The initial purchase comprised the mansion house and 58 acres of land to the south of Lower Addiscombe Road, but a further 30 acres to the north were subsequently acquired.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] New buildings were added, so that the mansion house, which originally housed the entire establishment, became a purely administrative block.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The additions included barracks, a chapel, a drawing and lecture hall, a hospital, a dining-hall, a sand-modelling hall, a gymnasium, and service facilities including a bakehouse, dairy, laundry, and brew-house.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In the early days cadets entered the Seminary between the ages of 131⁄2 and 16, and later between 15 and 18.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] They normally remained for 2 years (4 terms), although it was possible to pass the final examination within a shorter period.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The initial intake comprised 60 cadets, but numbers rose to about 75 a year, meaning that there were around 150 cadets in residence at any one time.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Cadets or their families were required to pay fees (£30 a year when the Seminary first opened; £50 a term by 1835), but these were heavily subsidised and represented only a proportion of the true costs of their education.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Initially, the main purpose of the Seminary was to train cadets for the Engineer or Artillery arms of the service, but as an experiment in 1816–17, and more permanently from 1827, "general service" cadets destined for the Infantry were admitted.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In all, some 3,600 cadets passed through Addiscombe during the years of its existence.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Of these, over 500 entered the Engineers, nearly 1,100 the Artillery, and about 2,000 the Infantry, some of whom subsequently transferred to the Cavalry.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Company paid well, and attracted some distinguished academic staff: John Shakespear published a standard Hindustani grammar, and Jonathan Cape was a Fellow of the Royal Society.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In practice, the emphasis was on mathematics, and the Seminary was criticised for not including more training in practical "military science".
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In the 1850s photography was also studied.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Bourne concludes that the Seminary was "not a true military college at all, but a militarised public school" – although he also judges that, by the standards of the age, its record as a military training school was not significantly worse than those of the establishments at Woolwich and Sandhurst.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Cadets were required to wear uniforms at all times, and were not permitted to go beyond the grounds or into Croydon without permission.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] However, they gained a reputation for indiscipline, and fights with the townspeople of Croydon were not infrequent.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] There was no corporal punishment, but in the early years, cadets could be punished by being incarcerated in the so-called "Black Hole", and fed on bread and water.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Until 1829 they worshipped regularly at Croydon Parish Church (marching there each Sunday in uniform, accompanied by their band): after that date they began to worship at the newly consecrated St James's Church, Addiscombe.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The day's events are described in one account as "a performance carefully prepared and rehearsed beforehand.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Its object was to make a favourable impression on a carefully selected audience".
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Public Examiner, who presided, was an eminent general (see list below); while the audience usually included some of the Directors of the East India Company, and often the Archbishop of Canterbury, who had a residence nearby at Addington Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] In 1848 the Seminary began awarding the Pollock Medal to the best cadet of the training season.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The award was named after Field Marshal Sir George Pollock.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Pollock Prize was transferred to the Royal Military Academy, Woolwich after Addiscombe was closed.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] Following the Indian Rebellion of 1857, the East India Company was wound up in 1858.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The college passed into government hands, becoming known as the Royal Indian Military College, Addiscombe, but continued to perform much the same function.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] With the amalgamation of the Royal and Indian services in 1861, there was initially a proposal that Addiscombe should be retained as a military college.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] However, the War Office decided that the establishments at Woolwich and Sandhurst were sufficient for their needs, and the college closed in June the same year.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The site was sold on 30 August 1861 for £33,600 to the British Land Company, who demolished most of the buildings.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] All that remain are two former professors' houses, "Ashleigh" and "India", on the corner of Clyde Road and Addiscombe Road; and the former gymnasium on Havelock Road, now private apartments.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The Land Company laid out five parallel roads over the greater part of the grounds, and built them up with villas.
[src:blue-plaque/addiscombe-military-seminary] The five roads – Outram, Havelock, Elgin, Clyde and Canning Roads – all took their names from soldiers and politicians prominent on the British side in the events of 1857–58, although none was in fact a college alumnus.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot is known as the *Home of the British Army*, a connection which led to its rapid growth from a small village to a Victorian town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The name is likely to have derived from alder trees found in the area (from the Old English 'alor-sceat' meaning copse, or projecting piece of land, featuring alder trees).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Any settlement, though not mentioned by name, would have been included as part of the Hundred of Crondall referred to in the Domesday Book of 1086.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Church of St Michael the Archangel is the parish church for the town and dates to the 12th century with later additions.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] There was almost certainly an earlier church on the site.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Cistercian monks from the nearby Waverley Abbey established granges or farms on their outlying estates, including one at Aldershot by 1175 for sheep grazing.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] We do not know when monks from the Abbey first came to Aldershot but the first documentary evidence is from 1287 when the Crondall Rental records that at 'Alreshate the Monks of Waverlye hold 31 acres of encroachment'.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] This area ran from the church of St Michael's down to the area around the present Brickfields Country Park while the grange itself was near the church.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] John Norden's map of Hampshire, published in the 1607 edition of William Camden's *Britannia*, indicates that Aldershot was a market town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The area was a vast stretch of sparsely populated common land, considered unsuitable for most forms of agriculture.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot, Crondall, Farnborough, and Yateley were all part of the manor of Crondall in the north-east corner of Hampshire.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Crondall manor is mentioned in the Domesday Survey in 1086.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was probably Scandinavian in origin, judging by the ruling family's practice of granting sole inheritance to the eldest child regardless of sex, rather than to the eldest son.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The first recorded mention of the manor of Aldershot is in 1573 in the will of Sir John White of Aldershot (c1512–1573), alderman of London who was knighted when he became Lord Mayor of London (1563-4).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] He left Aldershot Manor to his son Sir Robert White of Aldershot (died 1599).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] He, in turn, left the manor to be divided between his two daughters, Ellen the wife of Sir Richard Tichborne and Mary, the wife of Sir Walter Tichborne, brother of Richard.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The 18th-century jurist Charles Viner lived in the town and printed his *A General Abridgment of Law and Equity* on a press in his home.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In the 18th century, the stretch of the London to Winchester turnpike that passed through Aldershot between Bagshot and Farnham (now known as the Farnborough Road) was the scene of highway robberies.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At one time it had "almost as bad a reputation as Hounslow Heath".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Dick Turpin is said to have operated in the area having his headquarters nearby in Farnborough, and there were sightings of Spring-heeled Jack.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1854, at the time of the Crimean War, Aldershot Garrison was established as the first permanent training camp for the British Army.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] This led to a rapid expansion of Aldershot's population, going from 875 in 1851 to in excess of 16,000 by 1861 (including about 9,000 from the military).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Mrs Louisa Daniell arrived in the town at this time and set up her Soldiers' Home and Institute to cater for the spiritual needs of the soldiers and their families.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] During this period Holy Trinity church, the Presbyterian church, the Wesleyan church and Rotunda chapel were built in the town centre to cater for the spiritual needs of the increasing numbers of troops in the nearby camp and the growing civilian town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In August 1856, on her return from the Crimean War and "wishing to be with her sons in the Army", Mary Seacole with her business partner Thomas Day is said to have arrived in Aldershot where they attempted to open a canteen.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In her autobiography, Seacole wrote: 'We set to bravely at Aldershott to retrieve our fallen fortunes, and stem off the ruin originated in the Crimea, but all in vain...'.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The venture is believed to have failed through lack of funds and the two being declared bankrupt.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Aldershot Military Tattoo was an annual event dating back to 1894.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In the 1920s and 1930s, the Aldershot Command Searchlight Tattoo held at the Rushmoor Arena presented displays from all branches of the services, including performances lit by flame torches.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At one time the performances attracted crowds of up to 500,000 people.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Tattoo was organised to raise money for military charities.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] By the end of the 1930s, the event was raising around £40,000 annually.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Tattoo's modern format, the Army Show, was cancelled in 2010 by the Ministry of Defence due to budget cuts.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was briefly revived the following year and attracted 20,000 visitors.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 2012, it was styled as the Aldershot Garrison Show, a smaller free event held on Armed Forces Day.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Army Show was replaced in 2013 with a general Military Festival.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Events were held across the town, including an art exhibition, live music, sports events and film screenings.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1914, Aldershot had the largest army camp in the country, with 20% of the British Army being based in and around the town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot was home for two Infantry Divisions and a Cavalry Brigade in addition to large numbers of artillery, engineers, service corps and medical services.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At the start of World War I, the units based at Aldershot became the 1st Corps of the British Expeditionary Force, and soon tens of thousands of new recruits came to the large training centre in the Camp.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] This had a great effect on the civilian town as there was a great shortage of accommodation for the troops and many were billeted in local houses and schools.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot played a vital role in the formation of Kitchener's Army, providing the core of the Army from 1914 onwards as well as treating the wounded brought back from the trenches in France and Flanders.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Cambridge Military Hospital was the first base hospital to receive casualties directly from the Western Front and it was here that plastic surgery was first performed in the British Empire by Captain Gillies (later Sir Harold Gillies).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] From 1939 to 1945 during World War II, about 330,000 Canadian troops of the 1st, 2nd and 3rd Canadian Infantry Brigades passed through Aldershot for training before being deployed for the defence of the United Kingdom while much of the British Army was overseas.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Additional units of the Canadian Army followed later creating the largest force of British Commonwealth troops ever to be stationed in the UK at one time.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Aldershot riot of July 1945 caused considerable damage to the town centre when disgruntled Canadian troops tired of waiting to be repatriated rioted in the streets for two evenings.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In a gesture of forgiveness and goodwill, the Freedom of the Borough of Aldershot was conferred on the Canadian Army on 26 September 1945 in a ceremony held at the town's recreation ground.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In the following year Aldershot's military prison the 'Glasshouse' was burned down in prison riots.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] A substantial rebuilding of the barracks was carried out between 1961 and 1969 by the architecture and engineering firm Building Design Partnership.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The work was sped up under government pressure, and various new building technologies were employed with mixed success.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1974, Aldershot borough, which had been based at Aldershot Town Hall, merged with Farnborough urban district to form the Borough of Rushmoor under the provisions of the Local Government Act 1972.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] After a 2009 campaign, the British Government allowed veteran Gurkha soldiers who had served for more than four years, and their families, to settle in the UK.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The rise in the Nepalese population led Gerald Howarth, Conservative Member of Parliament for Aldershot, to request government assistance in expanding local public services to meet the needs of the growing population.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] On 22 February 1972, Aldershot experienced the first in a series of mainland IRA attacks.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Seven people, six of whom were civilian support staff, including five catering staff and a gardener were killed in a car bomb attack on the 16th Parachute Brigade headquarters mess.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The bombing was claimed by the Official IRA as revenge for the Bloody Sunday massacre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The only army officer killed was Captain Gerry Weston, a Catholic British Army chaplain.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] An area to be developed into a memorial garden was used to mark the 40th anniversary of the bombing in 2012.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Military Town is located between Aldershot and North Camp near Farnborough.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It is a garrison town that serves as the location for the military presence in the area.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It houses Aldershot Garrison's married quarters, barracks, Army playing fields and other sporting facilities.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The military town includes some local landmarks, such as the Aldershot Observatory, Aldershot Military Cemetery, the Union Building, the Royal Garrison Church and other churches.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Until 1993, the town served as headquarters for the Royal Corps of Transport and the Army Catering Corps, until they were merged into the Royal Logistic Corps and moved to Princess Royal Barracks, Deepcut.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Queen Victoria and Prince Albert showed a keen interest in the establishment and development of Aldershot as a garrison town in the 1850s, at the time of the Crimean War.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] They had a wooden Royal Pavilion built, where they would often stay when attending reviews of the army.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1860, Albert established and endowed the Prince Consort's Library, which still exists today.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] To celebrate Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee in 1897, 25,000 British and Colonial soldiers marched from Laffan's Plain near Farnborough, reviewed by Queen Victoria.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Colonial soldiers included men from Canada, India, Africa, Australia and New Zealand .
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Military Town comes under its own military jurisdiction.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was home to the Parachute Regiment from its formation in 1940 until it moved to Colchester Garrison in 2003.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Many famous people have been associated with the Military Town, including Charlie Chaplin, who made his first stage appearance in *The Canteen* theatre aged 5 in 1894, and Winston Churchill, who was based there in the late 19th century during his time in the Army.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The area also houses various military and regimental museums, including the Royal Army Physical Training Corps Museum and the Aldershot Military Museum, housed in a red-brick Victorian barracks.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Until December 2007, the Parachute Regiment and Airborne Forces Museum was in Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It has since moved to the Imperial War Museum Duxford.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The RAMC Memorial to the 314 men of the Royal Army Medical Corps who lost their lives in the Boer War of 1899-1902 is located at the top of Gun Hill.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] An outline planning application has been agreed for the redevelopment of some of the former Military Town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Aldershot Urban Extension will bring some 3,850 new homes, two new primary schools, a children's day-care centre, additional secondary school places, community facilities, waste recycling and landscaping to an area of 150 hectares.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 2013, the MoD announced a £100 million investment to expand Aldershot Garrison and bring 750 more service personnel and their families to settle in Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] A statue of the first Duke of Wellington mounted on his horse, Copenhagen, is situated on Round Hill behind the Royal Garrison Church.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The statue is 30 ft (9.1 m) high, 26 ft (7.9 m) from nose to tail, over 22 ft (6.7 m) in girth, weighs 40 tons and is intricately detailed including musculature and veins.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was designed and built by Matthew Cotes Wyatt who used recycled bronze from cannons that were captured at the Battle of Waterloo.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It took thirty men over three years to finish the project.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Originally, in 1846, the statue was erected at Hyde Park Corner, London on the Wellington Arch.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] However, Decimus Burton, architect of the arch, had tried to veto this plan for his preferred "figure in a four horse chariot".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Many agreed with Decimus Burton that the statue looked ridiculous since it was out of proportion.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was nicknamed "The Archduke" and was a popular topic in the satirical magazine *Punch*.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Queen Victoria claimed that the statue ruined the view of the skyline from Buckingham Palace, and she privately proposed that the statue be moved.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Duke, who had only sat for the sculptor on two or three occasions, suddenly became very attached to the statue and would not consider its removal from its arch.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1885, the Prince of Wales handed over the monument to Lieutenant General Anderson, the commander of the Aldershot Garrison.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The observatory is a circular red-brick building with a domed roof and it stands on Queen's Avenue.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Inside is a telescope, 8-inch refractor, mounted on a German-type equatorial mount with a clockwork drive.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The telescope and observatory building were a gift from aviation pioneer Patrick Young Alexander to the British Army, a fact which is recorded by a plaque near the observatory door.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It reads: "Presented to the Aldershot Army Corps by Patrick Y Alexander Esq 1906".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The former Wesleyan church on Grosvenor Road has a 100-foot tower that can be seen for miles around the town and which is described as "the only significant tower in the town".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Opened in 1877, the church served the Methodists of Aldershot for over 100 years and could seat 1,150 people until its closure in 1988.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Today, the original complex of church, Soldiers' Home and Hall, has been converted into offices, a dental surgery, gymnasium and homes.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Buddhist Centre is a Buddhist temple and community centre catering for the Buddhists of Aldershot and surrounding area, which is billed as the United Kingdom's first Buddhist community centre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] With the influx of large numbers of Nepalis into the area in recent years giving Rushmoor the largest Buddhist community in the United Kingdom, a temple and community centre to cater for their spiritual and secular needs was required.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The centre was formally opened on the High Street by the 14th Dalai Lama in June 2015.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] When a small party of NCOs and men of the Royal Engineers arrived in November 1853 in the area that is today Princes Gardens, they were the first soldiers to arrive in Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At this time, the area was heathland with the only building in sight being the Union Poor House, built in 1629 as a sub-manor for the Tichborne family and later used as the local workhouse and a school.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was one of five permanent local buildings purchased by the War Department in 1854 as part of the development of the new Aldershot Camp, and was used by the Army from 1854 to 1879 as No 2 Station Hospital.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In later years, it saw a variety of uses before being redeveloped as flats.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot railway station is a stop on the Alton Line; South Western Railway runs services between London Waterloo, Alton, Guildford and Ascot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot is close to several major roads, including the M3 and the A3.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Its nearest dual-carriageway roads are the A31 to the south, which heads east towards Guildford and the A3; to the east, the A331 which heads north towards Farnborough and the M3.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Bus services from Aldershot are provided by Stagecoach South.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Since the closure of Aldershot bus station in May 2023, passengers now access services at various on-street stops around the town centre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] National Express coach services operate between London Victoria and Portsmouth twice a day.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Farnborough Airport is located 5 miles (8.0 km) away, with Heathrow 29 miles (47 km) and Gatwick 43 miles (69 km) away.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] These will be joined by two new primary schools being built as part of the Aldershot Urban extension development of 3,850 houses.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] This development will also be served by a further 675 secondary school places being created at the Alderwood and Wavell schools.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Primary schools include Park Primary and St Michael's (C of E).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The infant schools are Talavera, Wellington Primary and Bell Vue Infant School.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Junior schools include: Newport County, Talavera, Wellington Secondary and St Joseph's Primary (Catholic).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot has only one secondary school, Alderwood School (formerly Heron Wood School and The Connaught School), though Ash Manor School, Farnham Heath End School, All Hallows Catholic School and The Wavell School are all local.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In the town's West End can be found Rowhill School, a special school for students of secondary age unable to attend mainstream schooling for a variety of reasons.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] There are also two private schools, Salesian College and Farnborough Hill School in nearby Farnborough.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The local press is the *Aldershot News & Mail*, a Surrey Advertiser Group broadsheet.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At the end of November 2017, the *Surrey-Hants Star Courier*, a free tabloid, ceased publication.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Following the demolition of the Theatre Royal and Hippodrome theatres in 1959 and 1961, the local council opened its own Princes Hall in 1973 as an entertainment venue.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Another entertainment venue and arts centre is the West End Centre on Queens Road which is popular for small-scale theatre, music and comedy.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Sam Leach, their then agent who wanted to become their manager, attempted to introduce the Beatles to London agents by promoting shows at The Palais Ballroom, on the corner of Perowne Street and Queens Road in Aldershot on 9 December 1961.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Leach wanted to organise a 'battle of the bands' between The Beatles and Ivor Jay and the Jaywalkers from London.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The show was not advertised properly and, as a result, only 18 people attended.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The local newspaper, *The Aldershot News*, failed to publish Leach's advertisement for the show.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In addition, Ivor Jay and the Jaywalkers failed to appear.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] However, the band and friends had their own fun after the show, drinking ale, playing football with bingo balls and dancing the foxtrot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The noise became so loud that a neighbour called the police who shut the event down.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] When interviewed in 1983 about the Aldershot gig, Paul McCartney described it as "the night we couldn't get arrested, but it wasn't for the lack of trying".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Weeks after this Brian Epstein became the group's manager.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Palace (previously The Palace Cinema, The Rhythm Station, Cheeks, Vox), influenced the rapid growth of the hardcore scene from 1992 to 1995.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] At the height of the club's popularity, a teenager's death from a suspected overdose of ecstasy was the catalyst that saw dance music leaving the club and had a negative impact on the hardcore dance scene in the Aldershot area.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Union Street and Wellington Street at the centre of the town's shopping district were pedestrianised in the 1970s when the Wellington Centre, a covered shopping centre, was built over the site of the town's former open-air market.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] As of 2020, Union Street East is undergoing regeneration; the project has been referred to as Union Yard.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 2003, a health check of the town centre concluded that, "Aldershot is experiencing promising signs of revitalisation, particularly in the shopping core".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] This revitalisation failed to materialise, with prominent traders such as Marks and Spencer leaving the town centre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 2005, Rushmoor Borough Council documented the percentage of vacant shops at 10%, 8% and 7% respectively for Union Street, the Wellington Centre and Wellington Street.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Westgate Leisure Park, which opened in 2012–2013 and which fronts onto Barrack Road, includes a Cineworld cinema, supermarkets and several chain restaurants.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot has many parks, playgrounds and open spaces for sport, play and leisure, including Aldershot Park, Brickfields Country Park, the Municipal Gardens, Manor Park and the Princes Gardens, the latter three a short walk from the town centre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The legacy of the Army has meant that the land for leisure use, as well as protected areas for flora and fauna, has been preserved over many years.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] On the Surrey border can be found Rowhill Nature Reserve, which is popular with nature-lovers, dog owners, walkers and joggers.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Sports facilities include the Rushmoor Gymnastics Academy, Aldershot Tennis Centre, Aldershot Bowling, Aldershot Pools and Lido, Aldershot Garrison Sports Centre, Alderwood Leisure Centre (formerly Connaught Leisure Centre) and Alpine Snow Sports (Dry Ski Centre).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Formerly the town also hosted short circuit motor racing including speedway and stock car racing.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Greyhound racing took place at Aldershot Stadium, and point-to-point racing at Tweseldown.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The running club AFD has produced some top runners.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Park hosts a number of sports facilities and organisations.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot is home to one of the most successful athletics clubs in British and European history, Aldershot, Farnham & District A.C..
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The club has produced many Olympians including Roger Hackney, Zola Budd, Lily Partridge and Steph Twell and specialises in middle–long distance running.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The home of AFD, as it is commonly known, is the Aldershot Military Stadium, Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Blackwater Valley Runners are a social running club and organise many local races.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Opened in 1930, Aldershot Lido is a traditional outdoor leisure pool (lido) that contains 1.5 million gallons of water situated on a 10-acre (4.0 ha) site.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The original land was a lake that had become overgrown with weeds.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was bought by the Borough Council in 1920 for £21,000 and was the focus of the council's improvement projects for the town.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Lido was the site of the swimming event in the modern pentathlon at the 1948 Summer Olympics.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The pool has extensive areas of shallow water for children to play including a large fountain at the centre.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It also has a diving area and water slides.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] There is an adjoining 25 m indoor pool that allows all year round swimming.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The local professional football team is Aldershot Town who compete in the National League.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Before 1992 the local club was Aldershot, which folded on 25 March 1992, while playing in the Football League Fourth Division.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The current club was formed shortly afterwards and achieved five promotions in its first 16 seasons to return to the Football League in 2008.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The previous Aldershot club's biggest success arguably came in 1987, just five years before closure, when they became the first team to win the Football League Fourth Division promotion play-offs, at the expense of a far bigger club – Wolverhampton Wanderers.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Since 1927, the main football ground in the town, and home of both teams, is the Recreation Ground, also known as *The Rec*.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It has a capacity for 7,100, of which 2,000 can be seated.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] A number of successful current and former footballers are from the Aldershot area, including Johnny Berry, who was born in the town in 1926.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] He played for Birmingham City and Manchester United before his playing career was ended by injuries sustained in the Munich air disaster on 6 February 1958.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] He had won three league title medals with Manchester United.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] He later returned to Aldershot and continued to live locally until he died in September 1994, at the age of 68.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Other footballers born in Aldershot include Craig Maskell (a striker for clubs including Southampton, Swindon Town and Reading) during the 1980s and 1990s, and Bruce Rioch (who played for clubs including Aston Villa and Derby County before managing clubs including Middlesbrough and Arsenal).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] On 25 October 2011, Aldershot Town played Manchester United at the Recreation Ground in the League Cup 4th round losing 3–0, their most successful run to-date in the Carling Cup.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Cricket Club is based in Aldershot Park in the town and plays in the Thames Valley Cricket League.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Army cricket matches have been played at the Officers Club Services Ground, which has also played host to home matches for Hampshire County Cricket Club.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Many of these matches held first-class status.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Cricket Club shares facilities with the successful Aldershot & Farnham Hockey Club which, in 2022, were looking for a more permanent base.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Formerly known as *Fleet RUFC*, the club started in 1991 as a pub side.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The club was renamed *Aldershot and Fleet RUFC* (A&F or the Stags) after their move in 2003 from Farnborough to their current home, Aldershot Park.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot & Fleet were successful in winning the RFU "Seal of Approval" Club of the Year 2008 for the southern region.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] They now play in the Hampshire 2 league.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Greyhound racing took place regularly at the now closed Aldershot Stadium in Tongham during the 1950s.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot Stadium was located in Oxenden Road, Tongham, and staged Stock Car racing for the first time on 30 October 1954.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The racing took place initially on a loose shale track inside the greyhound track; after Motorcycle speedway racing at the venue ceased, the shale track was replaced with a hard tarmaced surface.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The track was home to the Aldershot Knights for National League team racing in 1966 and again in 1971 and 1972.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The final meeting at Oxenden Road took place on 21 November 1992.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Immediately after this date, the site was cleared for construction of the A331 Blackwater Valley Road, which forms a by-pass for Aldershot and Farnborough.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1929, eight meetings were held at the 25 acres Aldershot Sports Stadium on Boxall's Lane.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The first of these was held on Wednesday 3 July 1929.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Speedway returned to Aldershot in 1950 at Aldershot Stadium.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Shots featured primarily in the third tier of the sport up to 1960.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Aldershot hosted three of the five events in the modern pentathlon at the 1948 London Olympics.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The swimming was held in Aldershot Lido, Maida Gymnasium hosted the fencing and the cross-country equestrian event was held at Tweseldown.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] All of the Olympic equestrian events, excluding the Prix des Nations, were also held at Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] It was announced on 15 January 2008 that the Aldershot Military Town had been chosen as the official training camp for the British Olympic team ahead of the 2012 Olympic Games in London.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] However, in April 2010, it was announced that Team GB would be training at Loughborough University.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] As of the May 2018 Rushmoor Borough Council elections and the May 2017 Hampshire County Council elections, of the 20 seats on Rushmoor Borough Council and Hampshire County Council covering Aldershot, the Conservatives hold 12 and Labour hold 8.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The town is represented in Parliament through the Aldershot constituency.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The current MP is Alex Baker of the Labour party.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] In 1894, a five-year old Charlie Chaplin made his first appearance on stage at the Canteen when his mother, a music-hall singer, lost her voice in the middle of a song and was booed offstage.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Chaplin was taken on stage by the stage-manager and left to entertain the audience with singing, dancing and imitations, including of his mother.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The barracks scenes in the 1968 film *The Charge of the Light Brigade*, starring David Hemmings and Trevor Howard, were filmed at the old West Cavalry Barracks (now largely demolished).
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The gates of the South Cavalry Barracks stood in as the prison gates for the 1960 film *Two-Way Stretch* starring Peter Sellers, Wilfrid Hyde-White and Lionel Jeffries.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Breakout (1959 film) used the East Cavalry Barracks.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The area was used for location filming of the 1970 *Doctor Who* episode "The Ambassadors of Death".
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Due to its architecture, Bruneval Barracks in Montgomery Lines was chosen as the location for snowy scenes in Kazan, Russia, at the end of the 2009 James Bond film *Quantum of Solace*.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] Parts of Aldershot's military training area were also used for the opening sequence in the 2002 James Bond film *Die Another Day*.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The Montgomery Lines were again used for Brad Pitt's film *World War Z* based on the novel by Max Brooks.
[src:blue-plaque/aldershot] The HBO series *House of the Dragon* filmed a number of scenes for the third episode on the Caesar's Camp military training ground on the border of Farnham and Aldershot.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Wilson was born in St Andrews, Fife, the son of Clara Fairfoul and Patrick Wilson, the town clerk of St Andrews.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He was educated at the University of St Andrews, graduating in 1733 with an MA.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He was first apprenticed to a physician in St Andrews where he became skilled in constructing mercury thermometers in glass.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1737, he left for London to make his fortune, He found work as assistant to a French surgeon-apothecary, which included caring for his patients.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] During this time he was introduced to Lord Isla who like Wilson was interested in astronomy, and Wilson constructed instruments for Isla during 1738.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] After visiting a type foundry with a friend in London, he had an idea for making better typefaces.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He and his friend John Baine returned to St Andrews in 1739, where they started a type foundry business in 1742.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] For example, in 1756 Wilson Greek typefaces were used to print classics of Greek literature.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1744, his type foundry moved to Camlachie, near Glasgow and in 1748 he was appointed type-founder to the University of Glasgow.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In the following year the partnership with Baine was dissolved.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He supplied types to the Foulis press making possible beautiful and artistic publications.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Among modern typefaces, Fontana, Scotch Roman, and Wilson Greek are based on types cut by Wilson.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1749, Wilson made the first recorded use of kites in meteorology with his lodger, a 23-year-old University of Glasgow student Thomas Melvill.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] They simultaneously measured air temperature at various levels above the ground with a train of kites.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Melvill went on to discover sodium light.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1757, Wilson invented hydrostatic bubbles, a form of hydrometer.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1760, with the support of his friend Lord Isla, the 3rd Duke of Argyle, Wilson was appointed to the new chair of practical astronomy at the University of Glasgow, as the University has recently completed the Macfarlane Observatory.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Wilson primarily made contributions to astronomy and meteorology, and posited that "what hinders the fixed stars from falling upon one another", the question that Newton had posed in his *Opticks* (1704), was that the entire universe rotated around its centre.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Wilson noted that sunspots viewed near the edge of the Sun's visible disk appear depressed below the solar surface, a phenomenon referred to as the Wilson effect.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] When the Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters announced a prize to be awarded for the best essay on the nature of solar spots, Wilson submitted an entry.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] On 18 February 1772 the Academy presented Wilson with a gold medal for his work on sunspots.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] The crater Wilson on the Moon is named for him, Ralph Elmer Wilson and C.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He, and his second son Patrick Wilson, were two of the founding members of the Royal Society of Edinburgh (RSE).
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] Patrick wrote a biographical article of his father which was published both in the *Transactions of the RSE* and *Edinburgh Journal of Science*.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1783 he was a joint founder of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] He died in Edinburgh on 16 October 1786.
[src:blue-plaque/alexander-wilson-astronomer] In 1740 Wilson married Jean, the daughter of William Sharp, a merchant in St Andrews.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] At first a private venture, in 1900 the owners planned to sell it and Alexandra Park for development.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A group of neighbouring local authorities managed to acquire it.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] An Act of Parliament created the Alexandra Palace and Park Trust.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Act required the trustees to maintain the building and the park, and make them available for the free use and recreation of the public forever.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The present trustee is the London Borough of Haringey, whose coat of arms shows lightning bolts depicting Alexandra Palace's pioneering role in the development of television.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1935 the trustees leased part of the Palace to the BBC for use as the production and transmission centre for their new television service.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Thus, in 1936, it became the home of the world's first regular public (then) "high-definition" television service.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The broadcasting system was 405-line monochrome analogue television – the first fully electronic television system to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Although other facilities soon superseded it after the Second World War, Alexandra Palace continued to be used by the BBC for many years, and its radio and television mast is still in use.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The original Studios A and B still survive in the southeast wing with their producers' galleries, and are used for exhibiting original historical television equipment.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The original Victorian Alexandra Palace Theatre with its stage machinery also survives and, as of 2019, is back in use.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The theatre and the stage structure are on English Heritage's Buildings at Risk register.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Palace became a listed building in 1996, at the instigation of the Hornsey Historical Society.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A planned commercial development of the building into a mixed leisure complex, including a hotel, a replacement ice-skating rink, a cinema, a ten-pin bowling alley and an exhibition centre, encountered opposition from public groups and was blocked by the High Court in 2007.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Great Hall and the West Hall are typically used for exhibitions, concerts and conferences.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] They are operated by the trading arm of the charitable trust that owns the building and the park on behalf of the public.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] There is also a pub, an ice rink, a palm court and a panoramic view of London.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 2013 Alexandra Park was declared a local nature reserve.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] It is also a Site of Borough Importance for Nature Conservation, Grade 1.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The nearest railway stations are Alexandra Palace, with Great Northern services from Moorgate, and the London Underground station Wood Green on the Piccadilly line.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Palace is also served by London Buses route W3, which is operated by Arriva London.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The "Palace of the People" was conceived by Owen Jones in 1859.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Great Northern Palace Company, established by 1860, initially failed to raise financing for the construction of the Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Construction materials were acquired and recycled from the large 1862 International Exhibition building in South Kensington after it was demolished (the government had declined to take it over).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Ltd. acquired the land of Tottenham Wood Farm for conversion to a park and to build the People's Palace on a site on a ridge more than 300 ft (91 m) high, part of Muswell Hill.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Park opened to the public on 23 July 1863.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The planned building was originally named "The Palace of the People"; it and its park were renamed to honour the popular new Princess of Wales, Alexandra of Denmark, who had married Prince Albert Edward (the future King Edward VII) on 10 March 1863.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] "The Palace of the People" and "The People's Palace" remained as alternative names.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In September 1865, construction commenced, but to a design by John Johnson and Alfred Meeson rather than implementing the glass structure initially proposed by Jones.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1871 work started on the Edgware, Highgate and London Railway to connect the site to Highgate station.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Work on both the railway and the Palace finished in 1873 and, on 24 May of that year, Alexandra Palace and Park opened.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The structure covers some 7.5 acres (3.0 ha).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace was built by Kelk and Lucas, who also built the Royal Albert Hall in South Kensington at around the same time.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Sims Reeves sang on the opening day before an audience of 102,000.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Only 16 days later a fire destroyed Alexandra Palace and also killed three members of staff.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Only the outer walls survived; a loan exhibition of a collection of English pottery and porcelain, comprising some 4,700 items of historic and intrinsic value, was also destroyed.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace, quickly rebuilt, reopened on 1 May 1875.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The new Alexandra Palace contained a concert hall, art galleries, a museum, a lecture hall, a library, a banqueting room and a large theatre.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The stage of the theatre incorporated machinery that enabled special-effects for the then-popular pantomimes and melodramas: performers could disappear, reappear and be propelled into the air.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The theatre was also used for political meetings.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] An open-air swimming pool was constructed at the base of the hill in the surrounding park; it is long since closed and little trace of it remains apart from some reeds.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The grounds included a horse-racing course with a grandstand, named the Alexandra Park Racecourse but nicknamed the "Frying Pan" or the "Pan Handle" because of its layout.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] It was London's only racecourse from 1868 until its closure in 1970.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] There were also a Japanese village, a switchback ride, a boating lake and a nine-hole pitch-and-putt golf course.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Park cricket and football clubs have also played within the grounds (in the middle of the old racecourse) since 1888.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A Henry Willis organ was installed in 1875, vandalised in 1918, and restored and reopened in 1929.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In its restored form Willis's masterpiece was declared by Marcel Dupré to be the finest concert-organ in Europe.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A committee was formed by Burt and the consortium managed to raise enough money to purchase them just in time.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1921 a plaque was erected at the entrance of the south terrace in honour of Burt.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace passed into the hands of the Greater London Council in 1967, with the proviso that it should be used entirely for charitable purpose.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The trusteeship was transferred to Haringey council in 1980.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] During the First World War the park was closed; the Palace and its grounds were first used as a refugee camp for displaced Belgians, and then later from 1915 to 1919 as an internment camp for German and Austrian civilians.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The theatre was greatly altered in the early 1920s, when the general manager, W.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] MacQueen-Pope, spent war reparation money on refurbishing the auditorium.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] He abandoned the understage machinery that had produced the effects necessary in Victorian melodrama; some of the machinery is preserved, and there is a project to restore some of it to working order.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] After these changes the theatre was leased by Archie Pitt, then husband of Gracie Fields, who appeared in the theatre.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Fields also drew an audience of 5,000 people to the hall for a charity event.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1935 the trustees leased part of the Palace to the BBC for use as the production and transmission centre for their new BBC Television service.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The antenna was designed by Charles Samuel Franklin of the Marconi Company.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The world's first public broadcasts of (then) "high-definition" television were made from Alexandra Palace in November 1936, an event which is alluded to by the rays in the modern coat of arms of the London Borough of Haringey.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Two competing systems, Marconi-EMI's 405-line system and John Logie Baird's 240-line system, were installed, each with its own broadcast studio and were transmitted on alternate weeks until the 405-line system was chosen in January 1937.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] After the BBC leased the eastern part of the Palace the theatre was only used for props storage space.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace continued as the BBC's main transmitting centre for London until 1956, interrupted only by the Second World War, when the transmitter found an alternative use jamming German bombers' navigation systems.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1944, a German doodlebug exploded just outside the organ end of the Great Hall and the Rose Window was blown in, leaving the organ exposed to the elements.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1947 some of the pieces of the shattered rose window were incorporated in a new design by architect E.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Spashett during renovation of bomb-damaged public buildings by the Ministry of Works.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] During the 1940s and 1950s the Palace also housed a public roller-skating rink and the Alexandra Palace Roller Skating Club.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In the early 1960s an outside broadcast was made from the top of the tower, in which the first passage of a satellite across the London sky was watched and described.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] It continued to be used for BBC News broadcasts until 1969, and for the Open University until 1981.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The antenna mast still stands and is used for local terrestrial television transmission, local commercial radio and Digital Audio Broadcasting.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The main London television transmitter is now at Crystal Palace in South London.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1977 the Greater London Council (GLC) considered a £20 million proposal to redevelop Alexandra Park into a multi-sport complex constructed around a shared football ground for two North London clubs, Arsenal and Tottenham Hotspur.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The 75,000-seat stadium would have required a new transit connection, either a monorail line or a branch of the Piccadilly line, and private funding.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The proposal was rejected by the GLC after local opposition cited the potential for hooliganism in the area.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Early in 1980 Haringey Council took over the trusteeship of Alexandra Palace from the GLC, insuring it for £31 million, intending to refurbish the building but just six months later, during Capital Radio's Jazz Festival, a fire started under the organ and quickly spread.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Again the outer walls survived and the eastern parts, including the theatre and the BBC Television studios and aerial mast, were saved.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Parts of the famous organ were destroyed, though it had been dismantled for repairs so some parts, including nearly all the pipework, were away from the building in store.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Some of the damage to the Palace was repaired immediately, but Haringey Council overspent on the restoration, creating a £30 million deficit.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace was reopened to the public in 1988 under a new management team headed by Louis Bizat.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Later the council was heavily criticised for the overspend in a report by Project Management International.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1991 the Attorney General stated that the overspending by the council as trustee was unlawful, and so could not be charged to the charity.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The council for some years did not accept this finding and instead maintained that the charity "owed" the council £30 million, charged compound interest on what it termed a "debt", which eventually rose to a claim of some £60 million, and to recoup it tried to offer the whole palace for sale.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] An ice rink was installed at Alexandra Palace in 1990.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Primarily intended for public skating, it has also housed ice hockey teams including the Harringay Racers, the Haringey Greyhounds, the London Racers and now the Haringey Huskies, as well as a figure skating club, the Alexandra Palace Amateur Ice Skating Club.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The first performances for about 70 years took place in the theatre, first in its foyer in June 2004, then, in July, in the theatre itself.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Although conditions were far from ideal, the audience was able to see the potential of this very large space.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Originally seating 3,000, it could not be licensed for more than a couple of hundred.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] It was intended that the theatre would reopen, but costly restoration would be required first.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] It will never again reach a seating capacity of 3,000, not least because one balcony was removed in the early part of the 20th century as a fire precaution when films started to be shown there.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A major season of the theatre company Complicité was planned for 2005, but the project, which would have included some repair and access work, was cancelled due to higher-than-anticipated costs.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In September 2009 the main hall at Alexandra Palace was allowed 2,000 more occupation, up to 10,250 ("still saddled by a £37 million debt it owes its guardian, Haringey Council").
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] A masterplan for the future of the site was drawn up in 2012, comprising six "big ideas" to restore and redevelop the Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The first of these to be implemented aimed to transform the derelict eastern end of the Palace, making the Victorian theatre and the historic BBC Studios accessible.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 2013 the Heritage Lottery Fund awarded a Round 1 pass to develop the proposals, creating a new entrance in the restored East Court, re-establishing the theatre as a flexible performance space and reopening the BBC Studios as a visitor attraction.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] There was controversy regarding plans to demolish the brick infills in the colonnade on the southeastern face of the building, which the BBC constructed after 1936 to form their television studios within.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Following a public consultation and advice from English Heritage, Planning and Listed Building Consent was given for the proposals, and in March 2015 HLF awarded Round 2 major grant funding.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 2018 Feilden Clegg Bradley Studios made a £27 million refurbishment of the long-abandoned Alexandra Palace Theatre and east wing.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 2018 it was announced that the Theatre would open for a BBC Proms performance on 1 September before officially reopening to the public on 1 December 2018 following the completion of the East Wing Restoration Project by the contractor Willmott Dixon.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The opening programme included performances from Dylan Moran, Horrible Histories, Gilbert & George, Gareth Malone and an evening of jazz presented by Ronnie Scott's.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] During the coronavirus pandemic Alexandra Palace was used by Edible London as a food distribution hub for local residents.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Palace has hosted a number of significant events.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Recurring events held there include the Great British Beer Festival (1977–1980), the Brit Awards (1993–1995), the PDC World Darts Championship (2008–present) and the Masters snooker tournament (2012–2020 and 2022–2025).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In November every year a large fireworks display is scheduled there as part of London's Bonfire Night celebrations.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The News of the World Darts Championship final stage was held at Alexandra Palace from 1963 to 1977.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In April 1967 a benefit event took place at the Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The 14 Hour Technicolor Dream, organised by the *International Times*, demonstrated the importance of the quickly developing Underground scene.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Although venues such as the UFO Club were hosting counter-cultural bands, this was certainly the largest indoor event at the time.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Performers included headlining act Pink Floyd as well as the Pretty Things, Savoy Brown, the Crazy World of Arthur Brown, Soft Machine, The Purple Gang, The Move and Sam Gopal's Dream (featuring Sam Gopal, Mick Hutchinson and Pete Sears).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] John Lennon attended, and Yoko Ono (who was soon to become Lennon's new romantic partner) presented her performance work "Cut Piece".
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1970 an Italian director, Lucio Fulci, filmed a segment of his giallo film *A Lizard in a Woman's Skin* here.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Alexandra Palace posed as a disused church.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The rock band Led Zeppelin played at Alexandra Palace's Grand Hall in two sell out performances on the evenings of the 22/23 December 1972.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Their concert tickets were priced at £1 each for the two-hour-long gig and were uniquely made available from specific Harlequin Record Shops within Central London.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1973 the Divine Light Mission held a "Festival of Love" there.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Also in 1973, British rock band Wishbone Ash played a Christmas concert at the Palace, billed as "Christmas at the Palace".
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The American band Grateful Dead played a series of three shows there between 9 and 11 September 1974; a recording of portions of all three shows was released as part of the Dick's Picks series in March 1997.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Campaign for Real Ale held the Great British Beer Festival there from 1977 to 1980 (the 1980 edition taking place in tents outside the fire-damaged Alexandra Palace).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] On the afternoon of 10 July 1980 (an accidental) fire destroyed the Great Hall, Banqueting Suite, Dressing Rooms and Ice Rink during contractors routine repairs and maintenance.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] From 27 July to 5 August 1973 The London Music Festival '73 was held here.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] After the fire the burnt-out shell of the great hall of Alexandra Palace was used as Victory Square in Michael Radford's 1984 film adaptation of George Orwell's novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Sinclair C5 battery electric vehicle was launched at the Palace in January 1985, one week after the closure of the 405-line television system that was inaugurated there 49 years earlier.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In November 1989 the Stone Roses performed a concert at Alexandra Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Hugh Cornwell played his last performance with the Stranglers at Alexandra Palace in August 1990.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] This was documented by the *Saturday Night, Sunday Morning* album and video.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Blur performed a major concert at the venue in October 1994 to promote their album *Parklife*.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The recording of the concert was released on video in February 1995 with the title *Showtime* and used as the basis for the video for the band's song "End of a Century".
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] From 1993 to 1995 the Brit Awards were hosted at Alexandra Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In November 1996 it was the venue for the annual MTV Europe Music Awards.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In 1996 the Palace hosted the inaugural London Model Engineering Exhibition which continued each year until 2021 when it was cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In April 2000 the funeral service of the Labour MP Bernie Grant took place at the Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The fourth Mind Sports Olympiad was held at Alexandra Palace in August 2000, with more than 4,000 competitors from around the world taking part in mind sports.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In December 2002 the *Miss World 2002* pageant was staged at the venue.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In June 2007 a Hackday event was hosted at Alexandra Palace by the BBC and Yahoo!
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] During the event the building was struck by lightning, causing the fire vents to open (and then get stuck open), and it rained inside the building.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Since December 2007 Alexandra Palace has hosted the PDC World Darts Championship, following 14 years from December 1993 to January 2007 of the tournament being held at the Circus Tavern in Purfleet, Essex.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Palace was previously home to the *News of the World* Darts Championship between 1963 and 1977.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] April 2008 saw the relaunch of the regular antiques fairs, now held four times a year, organised by International Antiques & Collectors Fairs (IACF).
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The band Portishead hosted one of two All Tomorrow's Parties festivals titled *I'll Be Your Mirror* in July 2011 at Alexandra Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The 50th anniversary programme of *Songs of Praise* was recorded there in September 2011 and broadcast the following month.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Since 2012 the Palace has been the venue for the Masters snooker tournament, held every January.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The only subsequent year it has not been held there was 2021, as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] During the 2012 Summer Olympics the Palace served as the official hospitality venue for the Dutch Olympic team.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In November 2012 it was the venue for the annual Warped Tour, a music and extreme sports festival.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The band Suede appeared in March 2013, playing one of the first dates in support of *Bloodsports*, their first new album in more than a decade.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In September 2013 Björk performed one of the final concerts of her Biophilia tour.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The show was the last concert to be held "in the round", a format that characterised the tour, and the first to be performed in this way at Alexandra Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The bootcamp stage for series 13 of *The X Factor* was filmed at the Alexandra Palace from 6 to 8 July 2016.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] In June 2020, Nick Cave recorded the live album and concert film *Idiot Prayer* in the West Hall.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] On the record, he performs songs from throughout his career solo on the piano.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] On 18 April 2021 London Grammar performed their third album, *Californian Soil*, live at Alexandra Palace.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge presented the inaugural Earthshot Prizes, with many celebrity guests, at Alexandra Palace on 17 October 2021.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Fontaines D.C. performed the last show of their 2021 UK tour at Alexandra Palace on 27 October 2021.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] On 11 November 2021 Bethesda Softworks hosted a special concert to celebrate the 10th anniversary release of *The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim*.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The performance by the London Symphony Orchestra and London Voices was livestreamed during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] Boxxer Promotions used the Palace for a Sunday special card which was headlined by rising prospect Adam Azim.
[src:blue-plaque/alexandra-palace] The event took place on 27 November 2022 and aired live on Sky Sports.
