[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson also focused on short lyrics, such as "Break, Break, Break", "The Charge of the Light Brigade", "Tears, Idle Tears", and "Crossing the Bar".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Much of his verse was based on classical mythological themes, such as "Ulysses" and "The Lotos-Eaters".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] "In Memoriam A.H.H." was written to commemorate his friend Arthur Hallam, a fellow poet and student at Trinity College, Cambridge, after he died of a stroke at the age of 22.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson also wrote notable blank verse, including *Idylls of the King*, "Ulysses", and "Tithonus".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] During his career, Tennyson attempted drama, but his plays enjoyed little success.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He is the ninth most frequently quoted writer in *The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations*.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Alfred Tennyson was born on 6 August 1809 in Somersby, Lincolnshire, England.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He was born into a successful middle-class family of minor landowning status distantly descended from John Savage, 2nd Earl Rivers, and Francis Leke, 1st Earl of Scarsdale.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] His father, George Clayton Tennyson, was an Anglican clergyman who served as rector of Somersby (1807–1831), also rector of Benniworth (1802–1831) and Bag Enderby, and vicar of Grimsby (1815).
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He raised a large family and "was a man of superior abilities and varied attainments, who tried his hand with fair success in architecture, painting, music, and poetry.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He was comfortably well off for a country clergyman, and his shrewd money management enabled the family to spend summers at Mablethorpe and Skegness on the eastern coast of England".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] George Clayton Tennyson was the elder son of the attorney and member of Parliament George Tennyson, of Bayons Manor and Usselby Hall, who had also inherited the estates of his mother's family, the Claytons, and married Mary, daughter and heiress of John Turner, of Caistor, Lincolnshire.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] George Clayton Tennyson was however pushed into a career in the church and passed over as heir in favour of his younger brother Charles.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Their mother, Elizabeth, was the daughter of Stephen Fytche, vicar of St James' Church, Louth (1764), and rector of Withcall (1780), a small village between Horncastle and Louth.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's father "carefully attended to the education and training of his children".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson, recalling the poetic influences of his youth, said, "as a boy I was an enormous admirer of Byron." Tennyson and two of his elder brothers were writing poetry in their teens, and a collection of poems by all three was published locally when Alfred was 17.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] One of those brothers, Charles Tennyson Turner, later married Louisa Sellwood, the younger sister of Alfred's future wife; the other was Frederick Tennyson.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Another of Tennyson's brothers, Edward Tennyson, was institutionalised at a private asylum.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson was a student of King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth, from 1816 to 1820.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He entered Trinity College, Cambridge, in 1827, where he joined a secret society called the Cambridge Apostles.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] A portrait of Tennyson by George Frederic Watts is in Trinity's collection.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] At Cambridge, he met Arthur Hallam and William Henry Brookfield, who became his closest friends.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] His first publication was a collection of "his boyish rhymes and those of his elder brother Charles" entitled *Poems by Two Brothers*, published in 1827.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1829, Tennyson was awarded the Chancellor's Gold Medal at Cambridge for one of his first pieces, "Timbuktu".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Reportedly, "it was thought to be no slight honour for a young man of twenty to win the chancellor's gold medal".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He published his first solo collection of poems, *Poems Chiefly Lyrical* in 1830.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] "Claribel" and "Mariana", which later took their place among Tennyson's most celebrated poems, were included in this volume.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Although decried by some critics as overly sentimental, his verse soon proved popular and brought Tennyson to the attention of well-known writers of the day, including Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In the spring of 1831, Tennyson's father died, requiring him to leave Cambridge before taking his degree.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He returned to the rectory, where he was permitted to live for another six years and shared responsibility for his widowed mother and the family.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Arthur Hallam came to stay with his family during the summer and became engaged to Tennyson's sister, Emilia Tennyson.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1833, Tennyson published his second book of poetry, which notably included the first version of "The Lady of Shalott".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The volume met heavy criticism, which so discouraged Tennyson that he did not publish again for ten years, although he did continue to write.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] That same year, Hallam died suddenly and unexpectedly after suffering a cerebral haemorrhage while on a holiday in Vienna.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Hallam's death had a profound effect on Tennyson and inspired several poems, including "In the Valley of Cauteretz" and "In Memoriam A.H.H.", a long poem detailing the "Way of the Soul".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson and his family were allowed to stay in the rectory for some time, but later moved to Beech Hill Park, High Beach, deep within Epping Forest, Essex, about 1837.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's son recalled: "there was a pond in the park on which in winter my father might be seen skating, sailing about on the ice in his long blue cloak.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He liked the nearness of London, whither he resorted to see his friends, but he could not stay in town even for a night, his mother being in such a nervous state that he did not like to leave her".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson befriended a Dr Allen, who ran a nearby asylum whose patients then included the poet John Clare.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] An unwise investment in Dr Allen's ecclesiastical wood-carving enterprise soon led to the loss of much of the family fortune, and led to a bout of serious depression.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] According to Tennyson's grandson Sir Charles Tennyson, Tennyson met Thomas Carlyle in 1839, if not earlier.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The pair began a lifelong friendship, and were famous smoking companions.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Some of Tennyson's work even bears the influence of Carlyle and his ideas.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson moved to London in 1840 and lived for a time at Chapel House, Twickenham.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] On 14 May 1842, while living modestly in London, Tennyson published the two-volume *Poems*, of which the first included works already published and the second was made up almost entirely of new poems.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] They met with immediate success; poems from this collection, such as "Locksley Hall", "Break, Break, Break", and "Ulysses", and a new version of "The Lady of Shalott", have met enduring fame.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] "The Princess: A Medley", a satire on women's education that came out in 1847, was also popular for its lyrics.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Gilbert later adapted and parodied the piece twice: in *The Princess* (1870) and in *Princess Ida* (1884).
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] It was in 1850 that Tennyson reached the pinnacle of his career, finally publishing his masterpiece, *In Memoriam A.H.H.*, dedicated to Hallam.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Later the same year, he was appointed Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom, succeeding William Wordsworth.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In the same year (on 13 June), Tennyson married Emily Sellwood, whom he had known since childhood, in the village of Shiplake.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] 11 August 1852)—named after his friend—and Lionel (b.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson rented Farringford House on the Isle of Wight in 1853, eventually buying it in 1856.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He eventually found that there were too many starstruck tourists who pestered him in Farringford, so he moved to Aldworth, in West Sussex in 1869.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] However, he retained Farringford and regularly returned there to spend the winters.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1850, after Wordsworth's death and Samuel Rogers' refusal, Tennyson was appointed Poet Laureate; Elizabeth Barrett Browning and Leigh Hunt had also been considered.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He held the position until his death in 1892, the longest tenure of any laureate.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson fulfilled the requirements of this position, such as by authoring a poem of greeting to Princess Alexandra of Denmark when she arrived in Britain to marry the future King Edward VII.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1855, Tennyson produced one of his best-known works, "The Charge of the Light Brigade", a dramatic tribute to the British cavalrymen involved in an ill-advised charge on 25 October 1854, during the Crimean War.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Other works written in the post of Poet Laureate include "Ode on the Death of the Duke of Wellington" and "Ode Sung at the Opening of the International Exhibition".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson declined a baronetcy offered him by Benjamin Disraeli in 1865 and 1868, finally accepting a peerage in 1883 at William Ewart Gladstone's earnest solicitation.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1884 Queen Victoria created him **Baron Tennyson**, of Aldworth in the County of Sussex and of Freshwater in the Isle of Wight.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He took his seat in the House of Lords on 11 March 1884.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson also wrote a substantial quantity of unofficial political verse, from the bellicose "Form, Riflemen, Form", on the French crisis of 1859 and the Creation of the Volunteer Force, to "Steersman, be not precipitate in thine act/of steering", deploring Gladstone's Home Rule Bill.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's family were Whigs by tradition and Tennyson's own politics fitted the Whig mould, although he would also vote for the Liberal Party after the Whigs dissolved.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Upon passage of the Reform Act 1832, Tennyson broke into a local church to ring the bells in celebration.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Virginia Woolf wrote a play called *Freshwater*, showing Tennyson as host to his friends Julia Margaret Cameron and G.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Colonel George Edward Gouraud, Thomas Edison's European agent, made sound recordings of Tennyson reading his own poetry, late in his life.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] They include recordings of "The Charge of the Light Brigade", and excerpts from "The splendour falls" (from The Princess), "Come into the garden" (from Maud), "Ask me no more", "Ode on the death of the Duke of Wellington" and "Lancelot and Elaine".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The sound quality is poor, as wax cylinder recordings usually are.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Towards the end of his life Tennyson revealed that his "religious beliefs also defied convention, leaning towards agnosticism and pandeism": In a characteristically Victorian manner, Tennyson combines a deep interest in contemporary science with an unorthodox, even idiosyncratic, Christian belief.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He wrote in *In Memoriam*: "There lives more faith in honest doubt, believe me, than in half the creeds." In *Maud*, 1855, he wrote: "The churches have killed their Christ".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In "Locksley Hall Sixty Years After", Tennyson wrote: "Christian love among the churches look'd the twin of heathen hate." In his play *Becket*, he wrote: "We are self-uncertain creatures, and we may, Yea, even when we know not, mix our spites and private hates with our defence of Heaven".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] 127): "I believe in Pantheism of a sort".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] His son's biography confirms that Tennyson was an unorthodox Christian, noting that Tennyson praised Giordano Bruno and Baruch Spinoza on his deathbed, saying of Bruno, "His view of God is in some ways mine", in 1892.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson continued writing into his eighties.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He died on 6 October 1892 at Aldworth, aged 83.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] A memorial was erected in All Saints' Church, Freshwater.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] His last words were, "Oh that press will have me now!".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson Down and the Tennyson Trail on the Isle of Wight are named after him, and a monument to him stands on top of Tennyson Down.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Lake Tennyson in New Zealand's high country, named by Frederick Weld, is assumed to be named after Tennyson.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He was succeeded as 2nd Baron Tennyson by his son Hallam, who produced an authorised biography of his father in 1897, and was later the second Governor-General of Australia.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Although Prince Albert, was largely responsible for Tennyson's appointment as Laureate, Queen Victoria became an ardent admirer of Tennyson's work, writing in her diary that she was "much soothed & pleased" by reading *In Memoriam A.H.H.* after Albert's death.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson met her a second time just over two decades later, on 7 August 1883, and the Queen told him what a comfort *In Memoriam A.H.H.* had been.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] As source material for his poetry, Tennyson used a wide range of subject matter, from medieval legends to classical myths and from domestic situations to observations of nature.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The influence of John Keats and other Romantic poets published before and during his childhood is evident from the richness of his imagery and descriptive writing.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The insistent beat of "Break, Break, Break" emphasises the relentless sadness of the subject matter.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's use of the musical qualities of words to emphasise his rhythms and meanings is sensitive.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson was a craftsman who polished and revised his manuscripts extensively, to the point where his efforts at self-editing were described by his contemporary Robert Browning as "insane", symptomatic of "mental infirmity".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] His complex compositional practice and frequent redrafting also demonstrates a dynamic relationship between images and words, as can be seen in the many notebooks he worked in.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Few poets have used such a variety of styles with such an exact understanding of metre; like many Victorian poets, he experimented in adapting the quantitative metres of Greek and Latin poetry to English.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He reflects the Victorian period of his maturity in his feeling for order and his tendency towards moralising.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] He also reflects a concern common among Victorian writers in being troubled by the conflict between religious faith and expanding scientific knowledge.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson possessed a strong poetic power, which his early readers often attributed to his "Englishness" and his masculinity.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Well-known among his longer works are *Maud* and *Idylls of the King*, the latter arguably the most famous Victorian adaptation of the legend of King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] A common thread of grief, melancholy, and loss connects much of his poetry (including "Mariana", "The Lotos Eaters", "Tears, Idle Tears", "In Memoriam"), possibly reflecting Tennyson's lifelong struggle with debilitating depression.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Eliot described Tennyson as "the saddest of all English poets", whose technical mastery of verse and language provided a "surface" to his poetry's "depths, to the abyss of sorrow".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's early poetry, with its medievalism and powerful visual imagery, was a major influence on the Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] In 1848 Dante Gabriel Rossetti and William Holman Hunt made a list of "Immortals", artistic heroes whom they admired, especially from literature, notably including John Keats and Tennyson, whose work would form subjects for PRB paintings.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] *The Lady of Shalott* alone was a subject for Rossetti, Hunt, John William Waterhouse (three versions), and Elizabeth Siddal.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] These are a difference of the arms of Thomas Tenison (1636–1715), Archbishop of Canterbury, themselves a difference of the arms of the 13th-century Denys family of Glamorgan and Siston in Gloucestershire, themselves a difference of the arms of Thomas de Cantilupe (c.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] 1218–1282), Bishop of Hereford, henceforth the arms of the See of Hereford; the name "Tennyson" signifies "Denys's son", although no connection between the two families is recorded.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Michael William Balfe's setting of "Come Into the Garden, Maud" was a popular success in 1857, as sung by the celebrated tenor Sims Reeves.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Arthur Somervell's *Maud* (1898) used thirteen poems (not all of them complete) for his song cycle, enough "to retain a cogent narrative".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Stephen Banfield believes it is "the nearest an English composer ever came to writing a substantial, Romantic song-cycle".
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Charles Villiers Stanford set "Crossing the Bar" for high voice and piano in April 1880, a year after the poem has been first published.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Maude Valérie White (four songs, 1885) and Liza Lehmann (10 songs, 1899) both composed song cycles selecting passages from *In Memoriam*.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Roger Quilter set "Now sleeps the crimson petal" (from *The Princess*) for voice and orchestra in 1905.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Ada Weigel Powers (1863-1947) used Tennyson’s text for her song “Elaine.” "The splendour falls on castle walls" (also from *The Princess*), has been set by many composers, including Arnold Bax, Benjamin Britten, Cecil Armstrong Gibbs, Gustav Holst, Stanford, Vaughan Williams and Charles Wood.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Karl Jenkins used several stanzas from Ring Out, Wild Bells in the last movement of his 1999 work The Armed Man: A Mass For Peace.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] Tennyson's "Ulysses" was quoted in the 2012 James Bond film *Skyfall*, with the character M (played by actress Judi Dench) reciting the poem.
[src:blue-plaque/alfred-lord-tennyson] The film's soundtrack also included an accompanying track, composed by Thomas Newman, that is titled "Tennyson".
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] A **blue plaque** is a permanent sign installed in a public place in the United Kingdom, Ireland, and certain other countries and territories, to commemorate a link between that location and a famous person, event, or former building on the site, serving as a historical marker.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The term is used in the United Kingdom in two senses.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The plaques erected are made in a variety of designs, shapes, materials and colours: some are blue, others are not.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] However, the term "blue plaque" is often used informally to encompass all such schemes.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The "official" scheme traces its origins to that launched in 1866 in London, on the initiative of the politician William Ewart, to mark the homes and workplaces of famous people.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The first such scheme in the world, it has provided inspiration and model for many others.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The scheme has been administered successively by the Society of Arts (1866–1901), the London County Council (1901–1965), the Greater London Council (1965–1986) and English Heritage (1986 to date).
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] It was initially focused on Greater London, although between 1998 and 2005, under a trial programme since discontinued, 34 plaques were erected elsewhere in England.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The Levelling-up and Regeneration Act 2023 extended the scheme to the whole of England though the plaques since erected outside of London have been put up by Historic England rather than English Heritage.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Many other plaque schemes have been initiated in the United Kingdom.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Some are restricted to a geographical area, others to a particular theme of historical commemoration.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] They are administered by a range of bodies including local authorities, civic societies, residents' associations and other organisations such as the Transport Trust, the Royal Society of Chemistry, the Music Hall Guild of Great Britain and America and the British Comic Society.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] There are commemorative plaque schemes throughout the world such as those in Paris, Rome, Oslo, and Dublin and in cities in Australia, Canada, the Philippines, Russia, and the United States.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] These take various forms and they are more likely to be known as commemorative plaques or historical markers.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The original blue plaque scheme was established by the Society of Arts in 1867, and since 1986 has been run by English Heritage.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] It is the oldest such scheme in the world.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] After being conceived by politician William Ewart in 1863, the scheme was initiated in 1866 by Ewart, Henry Cole and the Society of Arts (now the Royal Society of Arts), which erected plaques in a variety of shapes and colours.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The first plaque was unveiled in 1867 to commemorate Lord Byron at his birthplace, 24 Holles Street, Cavendish Square.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The earliest blue plaque to survive, also put up in 1867, commemorates Napoleon III in King Street, St James's.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Byron's plaque was blue, but the colour was changed by the manufacturer Minton, Hollins & Co to chocolate brown to save money.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The first woman to be honoured with a plaque was the actor Sarah Siddons in 1876.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The plaque, placed on her house in Marylebone, London, was retrieved when the house was demolished in 1905 and is now held in the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In total, the Society of Arts put up 35 plaques, fewer than half of which survive today.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The Society only erected one plaque within the square-mile of the City of London, that to Samuel Johnson on his house in Gough Square, in 1876.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1879, it was agreed that the City of London Corporation would be responsible for erecting plaques within the City to recognise its jurisdictional independence.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] This demarcation has remained ever since.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1901, the Society of Arts scheme was taken over by the London County Council (LCC), which gave much thought to the future design of the plaques.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] It was eventually decided to keep the basic shape and design of the Society's plaques, but to make them uniformly blue, with a laurel wreath and the LCC's title.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Though this design was used consistently from 1903 to 1938, some experimentation occurred in the 1920s, and plaques were made in bronze, stone and lead.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1921, the most common (blue) plaque design was revised, as it was discovered that glazed Royal Doulton stoneware was cheaper than the encaustic formerly used.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1938, a new plaque design was prepared by an unnamed student at the LCC's Central School of Arts and Crafts and was approved by the committee.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] It omitted the decorative elements of earlier plaque designs, and allowed for lettering to be better spaced and enlarged.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] A white border was added to the design shortly after, and this has remained the standard ever since.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] No plaques were erected between 1915 and 1919, or between 1940 and 1947, owing to the two world wars.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The LCC formalised the selection criteria for the scheme in 1954.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] When the LCC was abolished in 1965, the scheme was taken over by the Greater London Council (GLC).
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The principles of the scheme changed little, but now applied to the entire, much larger, administrative county of Greater London.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The GLC was also keen to broaden the range of people commemorated.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The GLC erected 252 plaques, the subjects including Sylvia Pankhurst, Samuel Coleridge-Taylor, and Mary Seacole.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1986, the GLC was disbanded and the blue plaques scheme passed to English Heritage.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] English Heritage erected more than 300 plaques in London.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In January 2013 English Heritage suspended proposals for plaques owing to funding cuts.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The National Trust's chairman stated that his organisation might step in to save the scheme.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In the event the scheme was relaunched by English Heritage in June 2014 with private funding (including support from a new donors' club, the Blue Plaques Club, and from property developer David Pearl).
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Four members of the advisory panel resigned over this transmutation.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Professor David Edgerton and author and critic Gillian Darley were concerned that the scheme had been "reduced to a marketing tool for English Heritage".
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The vice chair Dr Celina Fox and Dr Margaret Pelling stated that the scheme was "being dismantled and its previous achievements discredited".
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In April 2015, English Heritage was divided into two parts, Historic England (a statutory body), and the new English Heritage Trust (a charity, which took over the English Heritage operating name and logo).
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Responsibility for the blue plaque scheme passed to the English Heritage Trust.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The 1,000th plaque, marking the offices of the Women's Freedom League, 1908–1915, was unveiled in 2023.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In cases of foreigners and overseas visitors, candidates should be of international reputation or significant standing in their own country.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Other schemes have different criteria, which are often less restrictive: in particular, it is common under other schemes for plaques to be erected to mark the sites of demolished buildings.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Almost all the proposals for English Heritage blue plaques are made by members of the public who write or email the organisation before submitting a formal proposal.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] English Heritage's in-house historian researches the proposal, and the Blue Plaques Panel advises on which suggestions should be successful.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] This is composed of 12 people from various disciplines from across the country.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The panel is chaired by Professor William Whyte.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Other members (as at September 2023) include Richard J.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Aldrich, Mihir Bose, Andrew Graham-Dixon, Claire Harman, Gus Casely-Hayford and Amy Lame.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The actor and broadcaster Stephen Fry was formerly a member of the panel, and wrote the foreword to the book *Lived in London: Blue Plaques and the Stories Behind Them* (2009).
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Roughly a third of proposals are approved in principle, and are placed on a shortlist.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Because the scheme is so popular, and because a lot of detailed research has to be carried out, it takes about three years for each case to reach the top of the shortlist.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Proposals not taken forward can only be re-proposed once 10 years have elapsed.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] From 1923, soon after the standardisation of the design in 1921, the plaques were manufactured by Royal Doulton which continued their production until 1955.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] From 1984 until 2015 they were made by Frank Ashworth at his studio in Cornwall, and were then inscribed by his wife.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] From 1955 to 1985 the lettering for the plaques was designed in the Roman lettering style by Henry Hooper.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Since 2015, the plaques have been made by Ned Heywood, a potter, at his workshop in Chepstow, Wales.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] A small minority of GLC and English Heritage plaques have been erected to commemorate events which took place at particular locations rather than the famous people who lived there.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 1998, English Heritage initiated a trial national plaques scheme, and over the following years erected 34 plaques in Birmingham, Merseyside, Southampton and Portsmouth.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The scheme was discontinued in 2005, although English Heritage continued to provide advice and guidance to individuals and organisations outside of London wanting to develop local schemes.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In September 2023 the Department for Culture, Media and Sport announced the reintroduction of a national scheme, with Historic England as the lead developer.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] From mid 2024, the public were invited to submit nominations, with eligibility criteria including a minimum of 20 years having passed since the death of the nominee, who must have made a significant contribution to human welfare or happiness.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] At least one surviving building must be associated with the nominee in a form that they would have recognised and the building must be visible from the public highway.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The first plaque in the scheme was unveiled in Ilkley, West Yorkshire on 23 February 2024, commemorating Daphne Steele, first Black matron in the National Health Service in 1964.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] On 24 May 2024, a blue plaque commemorating the childhood home of musician George Harrison in Liverpool was unveiled.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The popularity of English Heritage's London blue plaques scheme has meant that a number of comparable schemes have been established elsewhere in the United Kingdom.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Many of these schemes also use blue plaques, often manufactured in metal or plastic rather than the ceramic used in London, but some feature plaques of different colours and shapes.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 2012, English Heritage published a register of plaque schemes run by other organisations across England.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The criteria for selection varies greatly.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Many schemes treat plaques primarily as memorials and place them on the sites of former buildings, in contrast to the strict English Heritage policy of only installing a plaque on the actual building in which a famous person lived or an event took place.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The Corporation of London continues to run its own plaque scheme for the City of London, where English Heritage does not erect plaques.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] City of London plaques are blue and ceramic, but are rectangular in shape and carry the City of London coat of arms.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Because of the rapidity of change in the built environment within the City, a high proportion of Corporation of London plaques mark the sites of former buildings.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Many of the 32 London boroughs also now have their own schemes, running alongside the English Heritage scheme.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Westminster City Council runs a **green plaque** scheme, each plaque being sponsored by a group with a particular interest in its subject.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The London Borough of Southwark started its own blue plaque scheme in 2003, under which the borough awards plaques through popular vote following public nomination: living people may be commemorated.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The London Borough of Islington has a similar green heritage plaque scheme, initiated in 2010.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Other plaques may be erected by smaller groups, such as residents' associations.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In 2007 the Hampstead Garden Suburb Residents Association erected a blue plaque in memory of Prime Minister Harold Wilson at 12 Southway as part of the suburb's centenary celebrations.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Historic Environment Scotland, the Scottish heritage agency, has previously operated a national commemorative plaques scheme but, as of 2023, this was inactive.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Regional schemes are run by local authorities.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Wales does not operate a national blue plaque scheme, although in 2022 Andrew RT Davies, leader of the Welsh Conservative Group in the Senedd, called for the introduction of a country-wide approach.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Regional schemes are operated by local authorities such as Swansea and civic societies.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] The Purple Plaques scheme is a national scheme (across Wales) that aims to commemorate women whose lives have had a significant and long-lasting impact.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] In Northern Ireland, Belfast City Council and the Ulster History Circle are among a small number of groups administering blue plaques.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Established in 1983, the Ulster History Circle has erected around 260.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Its scope extends into the Republic of Ireland, covering all nine counties of Ulster, the northern province in Ireland.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] Elsewhere in the Republic, schemes are operated through local authorities and civic societies.
[src:blue-plaque/blue-plaque] There also exist several nationwide schemes sponsored by special-interest bodies, which erect plaques at sites or buildings with historical associations within their particular sphere of activity.
